.TH DATE(1),User Commands,DATE(1)

.SH NAME
date - print the current date and time

.SH SYNOPSIS
date [+format]

.SH DESCRIPTION
date prints the current date and time read from the system clock.
With no argument, it uses the default format "%a %b %e %H:%M:%S %Z %Y".

If an argument is given, it must begin with a + sign.
The rest of the string is treated as a format specifier in which %-escapes are substituted with date fields and all other characters are copied verbatim.

.SH FORMAT SPECIFIERS
%a: abbreviated weekday name (Sun, Mon, ...)

%A: full weekday name

%b, %h: abbreviated month name (Jan, Feb, ...)

%B: full month name

%d: day of month, two-digit zero-padded

%D, %x: MM/DD/YYYY

%e: day of month, space-padded

%H: hour (00-23)

%I: hour (01-12)

%j: day of year, three-digit zero-padded

%m: month (01-12)

%M: minute (00-59)

%p: AM or PM

%r: 12-hour time with AM/PM

%S: second (00-59)

%T, %X: HH:MM:SS

%u: day of week (1=Monday, 7=Sunday)

%U: week of year, Sunday-based

%V: week of year, ISO-style (Monday-based)

%w: day of week (0=Sunday, 6=Saturday)

%y: year, last two digits

%Y: year, four digits

%Z: time zone (always empty on cx16os)

%n: newline

%t: tab

%%: literal percent sign

Unrecognized % escapes print a literal % followed by the escape character.

.SH EXAMPLES
Default output:

$ date

ISO-style date:

$ date +%Y-%m-%d

24-hour time only:

$ date +%T

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: Date printed.

1: More than one operand given, or format string does not begin with +.
